  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Background Ambient airborne particulate material (PM) is defined according the aerodynamic
      diameter into coarse, fine, and ultrafine or &quot;nano&quot; sized particles ranging between 2.5-10 µm
      (coarse), &lt;2.5 µm (fine), and &lt;0.1 µm (nano(. Many studies have examined particle effect on
      respiratory health in children, mainly by environmental monitoring of coarse and fine
      particles. Biological assessment of individual exposure to nano sized particles in
      correlation to adverse health effect was not previously studied.

      Hypothesis individual exposure to nano sized particles in children is associated with
      reduction in forced expiratory volume at one second.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
